<h3>William Sharp (Leon Schleifer), Satiric Wizard of the Pen (1900-1961)</h3>

<p class="one">Emerging on the New York artistic scene just before the start of the 
Second World War, William Sharp was an Austrian-born Jew (born Leon Schleifer) whose 
satirical cartoons of the Nazis and their flamboyant leader during the 1920s made him 
<em>persona non grata</em> in Germany, compelling him to flee the country in 1933 under 
threat of imprisonment if he remained. Arriving in the United States in 1934, he adopted 
the English surname "Sharp," perhaps to reflect his precision as a draftsman and the 
acuteness of his visual satire. Six years later, he became an American citizen and 
comfortable denizen of Forrest Hills, NY. He was fascinated by a disparate range of 
contemporary figures from Sir Winston Churchill to mobster Frank Costello, but was also a 
recorder of daily life in Queens, including society ladies, baseball players, and boxers 
as the subjects of his vignettes of urban life. His first American commission was for the 
Hearst newspaper chain, sketching the 1934 trial of Bruno Richard Hauptmann, accused of 
kidnapping and murdering Charles Lindbergh's infant son. He went on to cover a long 
series of trials, including those of Alger Hiss, accused of espionage and convicted of 
perjury, and of Julius and Ethel Rosenberg, who were executed for spying. There followed 
assignments from <span class="book">Life</span>, <span class="book">The New York 
Post</span>, <span class="book">The Daily Mirror</span>, <span class="book">The New York 
Times Magazine</span>, and other magazines and journals. He also became a sought-after 
book illustrator, producing memorable images for <span class="book">The Wall</span> 
(1950) by John Hersey, the story of the Warsaw ghetto uprising during the Nazi occupation 
of Poland and Dostoyevsky's <span class="book">The Brothers Karamozov</span>, as well as 
such classics as Edgar Allen Poe's <span class="book">Tales of Mystery and 
Imagination</span> and the Random House <span class="book">Treasury of Stephen 
Foster</span> (1946), as well as  the short stories of Ernest Hemingway and Thomas Mann.  
His illustrations for <span class="book">The Diary of Samuel Pepys</span>, and a volume 
of Dickens brought him considerable acclaim. After his work on Wilkie Collins's <span 
class="book">The Moonstone</span> in 1944, he illustrated the Heritage Press's biography 
of Benjamin Franklin in 1951.</p>

